    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Garden goblins, I mean, it's just a colloquialism I use to describe the unexpected problems that can arise in the garden. But, I suppose it's a bit of a stretch, even for a goblin enthusiast like myself.\n\nIn that case, let's focus on the issue at hand. Yellowing leaves on the bottom of the plant can be a sign of nutrient deficiencies, particularly nitrogen, iron, or magnesium. It's possible that your soil is lacking one of these essential nutrients, which can be caused by a variety of factors, including poor soil quality, pH imbalances, or over-fertilization.\n\nYou can try checking the pH level of your soil and adjusting it if necessary. A pH range of 6.0 to 6.8 is ideal for most tomato plants. Also, consider getting a soil test to determine the nutrient levels and identify any potential deficiencies.\n\nIt's also worth noting that some tomato varieties are more prone to yellowing leaves than others. If you can provide me with more information about your plant, such as the variety and growing conditions, I may be able to offer more specific advice.",
